data.content:
Yes! For simple inline data, use `[DataRow]` — it's cleaner and avoids the `object[]` indirection:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

If you need **complex or computed data** (objects, non-constants), keep `DynamicData` but add type safety with tuples:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key tradeoffs:**

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| `[DataRow]` | Simplest, no extra property | Values must be compile-time constants |
| `DynamicData` + tuples | Type-safe, supports computed values | Slightly more ceremony |
| `DynamicData` + `object[]` | Flexible | No type safety, easy to mix up args |

**Recommendation:** Use `[DataRow]` when all values are constants (strings, bools, ints). Switch to `DynamicData` with tuples only when you need runtime-constructed data.
